<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n53136b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53136b">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53136b"> 136(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> lol (rose): led (red) / A(kadem) Fikup / ne(zessid) Nelij <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53136b"><li>FW 34.31 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n53136b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n53136b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53136b">MS BL 47476a-19</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:035 <a name="bd9" href="../../FF/fdra/bda.htm#bd9">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/bd9.htm#n53136b">Draft: I.2&sect;1.9</a>/2.9/3.9</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Jespersen explains that, Volap&uuml;k being highly inflectional, each stem begins and ends with a consonant, thus &lsquo;Academy&rsquo; becomes <i>Kadem</i>. As the letter /r/ is (for some reason) eschewed, &lsquo;red&rsquo; becomes <i>led</i>. As /s/ is associated with the idea of plurality, it is elided in Volap&uuml;k from terminations in the singular, thus &lsquo;rose&rsquo; becomes <i>lol</i>. As /ne-/ is indicative of negation, it is avoided also, thus &lsquo;necessity&rsquo; is shortened to <i>zes&uuml;d</i>. In Volap&uuml;k the word &lsquo;English&rsquo; becomes <i>Nelij</i>, pronounced &lsquo;Nelish&rsquo;.]</font> <font color="green">[Index: Part 3]</font> <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJIL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJIL"><cite title="source">An International Language</cite></a> (1928) 34</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
